NATION BRIEFS																																												Mumbai, Nov. 4: A fire broke out on the 13th floor of Express Towers at Nariman Point, Mumbais premier business district, this evening. There were no casualties.																																												Five fire tenders battled the blaze, which started in the offices of advertising agency Lintas around 4.45pm, for more than three hours, according to fire brigade officials. Since it was a Sunday, most offices in the 25-storey building were closed.																																												 Mumbai (PTI): The Maharashtra consumer disputes redressal commission has directed a travel agency and a hotel to compensate a tourist for not offering the services mentioned in their brochures.																																												New Delhi (PTI): The central administrative tribunal has held that leave cannot be taken as a matter of right. The tribunal, hearing a petition of a central government teacher, said the period of absence of the teacher should be treated as not spent on duty.																																												Melbourne (PTI): Jayant Patel, the surgeon facing charges over deaths of patients, plans to fight his extradition to Australia from the US, a friend has said. Vijay Mehta, a Texas-based surgeon, said Patel was preparing for a court battle that could last more than four years, Sydney Morning Herald said.																																												Madurai (PTI): The Madurai bench of Madras High Court has ruled that the water connection to a house could be cut without a notice if a consumer was found illegally drawing water. The bench said the principle of natural justice would not apply in such a case. The consumer violated the governments ban on drawing water from civic pipelines. 																																												Mangalore (PTI): Two tiger skins and a panther skin, together worth Rs 6 lakh, were seized from wildlife traders on Saturday, police said. Five persons have been arrested from Kadaba, 70km from here. 
